class Solution {
    vector<int> prefix;
public:
    Solution(vector<int>& w) {
        prefix.reserve(w.size());
        int sum = 0;
        for (int weight : w) {
            sum += weight;
            prefix.push_back(sum);
        }
    }

    int pickIndex() {
        int total = prefix.back();
        int target = rand() % total;
        return upper_bound(prefix.begin(), prefix.end(), target) - prefix.begin();
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log N) per pickIndex, O(N) for constructor
space complexity: O(N)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Prefix-sum array converts weights into cumulative ranges; binary search (via upper_bound) maps a uniform random number to the correct index in logarithmic time. Constructor is linear, pickIndex is logarithmic, both optimal for the constraints.

